  "message": "test(fuzz): add 12 raptorq_decoder corpus seeds for shape coverage\n\nExtend the existing raptorq_decoder fuzz seed corpus (which had\nonly the three legacy `seed_*_payload.bin` blobs) with 12\nadditional structured seeds chosen to give libFuzzer immediate\nreach into the decoder's interesting size and corruption shapes\nwithout having to discover them from random bytes.\n\nSize-axis seeds:\n- `tiny_artifact` (8 B): below the FEC header threshold; drives\n  the early-return / \"input too small\" branch.\n- `minimal_artifact` (17 B): just past the OTI header so the\n  decoder enters the symbol-walk path with the smallest valid\n  payload.\n- `medium_artifact` (107 B): mid-sized payload to land in the\n  common-case decode path.\n- `large_artifact` (509 B): exercises multi-symbol assembly and\n  block budgeting on a non-trivial payload.\n- `min_symbol_size` / `max_symbol_size` (71 B each): pin the\n  symbol_size parameter to opposite ends of the legal range so\n  the symbol-table allocator paths are seeded from both\n  extremes.\n- `large_block_size` (208 B): targets the block-count branch\n  that's hard to reach via byte-level mutation alone.\n\nCorruption-axis seeds:\n- `corrupt_first_byte` / `corrupt_middle` (59 B each): byte-flips\n  in the OTI header vs payload body so the decoder's two\n  separate validation paths each see a poisoned input from the\n  start.\n- `binary_content` (39 B): non-printable bytes outside the usual\n  ASCII patterns the mutator tends to produce, helps the\n  fuzzer's coverage heuristic stay focused on structure\n  instead of charset.\n- `zeros_artifact` (23 B): all-zero payload, the canonical\n  \"everything is the OTI default\" input.\n- `high_repair_overhead` (87 B): seed with an inflated repair\n  symbol count so the high-overhead reconstruction path is\n  reachable from iteration zero.\n\nNet effect: the raptorq_decoder corpus now covers six payload\nsize classes and four corruption classes from the start of a\nfresh fuzz run, instead of the three uninstrumented binary\nblobs we had previously.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>",
